\begin{IDEAS}
1. **Title: Degeneracy Breaking via Spectral Shape Analysis**
Research Objective: Investigate whether the shape of the cumulative distribution function $N(>\tau)$—rather than just the total count $N_{abs}$—can break the degeneracy between DM-baryon structure suppression and astrophysical uncertainties like IGM heating or reionization history. By analyzing the differential slope of the $N(>\tau)$ curve, this study aims to determine if scattering-induced suppression leaves a unique "fingerprint" on the distribution of small-scale absorption troughs.

2. **Title: Optimal Redshift Windows for Dark Matter Detection**
Research Objective: Determine the redshift range $z \in [7, 15]$ that maximizes the signal-to-noise ratio for detecting DM-baryon scattering cross-sections. This project will quantify the tension between declining absorber abundance at high $z$ and the increasing relative impact of structure suppression on the remaining small-scale halos.

3. **Title: Cross-Correlation of Forest Statistics and Global Signal Constraints**
Research Objective: Assess the complementarity between 21 cm forest statistics and global 21 cm signal constraints by mapping their respective parameter degeneracies. The objective is to quantify how much of the parameter space for DM-baryon interactions is uniquely constrained by the forest’s sensitivity to the halo mass function cutoff compared to the thermal sensitivity of the global signal.

4. **Title: Impact of Subhalo Population Dynamics on Scattering Signatures**
Research Objective: Quantify how the presence of subhalos—modeled in the HAYASHI framework—alters the sensitivity of the 21 cm forest to DM-baryon scattering. This study explores whether the subhalo contribution masks or amplifies the signature of structure suppression at different redshifts, effectively testing the robustness of the forest as a probe of small-scale DM physics.

5. **Title: Sensitivity Mapping for Velocity-Dependent Cross-Sections**
Research Objective: Derive the sensitivity of 21 cm forest observations to $n=-4$ (Coulomb-like) DM-baryon scattering models. This project aims to translate the redshift-evolving suppression of $N_{abs}$ into specific constraints on the velocity-dependent cross-section, contrasting these findings with velocity-independent ($n=0$) baseline predictions.

6. **Title: Statistical Limits of Sparse Line-of-Sight Sampling**
Research Objective: Evaluate the minimum number of high-redshift radio sources required to distinguish between CDM and various DM-baryon interaction models at specific confidence intervals. By treating the number of lines of sight as a variable, this work establishes the observational threshold required for SKA to make a statistically significant detection of structure suppression.

7. **Title: Multi-Scale Power Spectrum Reconstruction from Forest Troughs**
Research Objective: Determine if the cumulative absorption distribution $N(>\tau)$ can be inverted to reconstruct the matter power spectrum on scales sensitive to DM-baryon scattering. The objective is to define the mapping between the observed distribution of absorption troughs and the underlying suppression of the primordial power spectrum.

8. **Title: Sensitivity of the 21 cm Forest to Warm Dark Matter (WDM) Mimicry**
Research Objective: Compare the observational signatures of DM-baryon scattering-induced structure suppression against standard WDM models. This study aims to identify whether the redshift-dependent evolution of $N_{abs}$ provides enough diagnostic power to distinguish between scattering-induced suppression and the free-streaming cutoff inherent in thermal relic dark matter.

9. **Title: Quantifying the Saturation Limit of Thermal Effects**
Research Objective: Analyze the theoretical saturation point where further cooling of the IGM ceases to influence the optical depth of the 21 cm forest. By identifying the exact conditions under which $f_{cool}$ becomes irrelevant to $N_{abs}$, this study isolates the precise regime where the forest becomes a "pure" probe of mechanical structure suppression rather than thermal history.

10. **Title: Error Propagation in Semianalytic Halo Modeling**
Research Objective: Assess the sensitivity of the DM-baryon scattering signature to uncertainties in the underlying halo mass function and baryon fraction models. The goal is to establish the "systematic floor" of the 21 cm forest method, defining how accurately we must understand standard cosmology before we can claim a detection of DM-baryon scattering.
\end{IDEAS}


