\begin{IDEA}
**Title**: Probing the Dark Matter-Baryon Scattering Sensitivity Frontier: A 21 cm Forest Analysis of Structure Suppression vs. Thermal Channels

**Description**: This study establishes the 21 cm forest as a precision probe of the DM-baryon structure suppression channel, moving beyond the thermal limitations of the global 21 cm signal. Utilizing the HAYASHI semianalytic framework, we quantify the sensitivity of the cumulative absorber count $N(>\tau)$ to the half-mode mass cutoff $M_{cut}$, mapping these results to the velocity-independent and Coulomb-like scattering cross-sections $\sigma_0/m_\chi$. We demonstrate that the 21 cm forest provides a distinct, high-significance constraint on $M_{cut}$ due to the factor of 3–14x suppression in $N_{abs}$ observed across $z=7–15$. By performing a Fisher forecast for SKA-era observations, we determine the minimum detectable $\sigma_0/m_\chi$ and prove that the forest's sensitivity is dominated by structure suppression rather than thermal cooling, which is found to be statistically negligible ($<1\%$) in this redshift range. This analysis defines the optimal redshift window ($z \sim 10$) for constraining DM-baryon interactions and establishes the 21 cm forest as a uniquely sensitive tool for probing small-scale DM physics compared to current CMB and global signal constraints.
\end{IDEA}


